\section*{Answer the following \hfill 1x5=5}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] What is the purpose of the `void` keyword in C?
    \item[(b)] What is the size of the `char` data type in C?
    \item[(c)] How do you declare a constant integer in C?
    \item[(d)] Write the syntax for a `while` loop in C.
    \item[(e)] What is the purpose of the `include` directive in C?
\end{enumerate}

\vspace{0.5cm}

\section*{Answer the following questions \hfill 2x5=10}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] Explain the difference between `struct` and `union` in C with an example.
    \item[(b)] What is the significance of the `break` and `continue` statements in loops? Provide examples.
    \item[(c)] Write a C program to reverse the digits of a number.
    \item[(d)] What is the difference between `++i` and `i++` in C? Provide examples.
    \item[(e)] How does C handle multi-dimensional arrays? Provide an example.
\end{enumerate}

\vspace{0.5cm}

\section*{Answer any three of the following \hfill 5x3=15}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] Write a C program to find the largest element in an array.
    \item[(b)] Explain the concept of recursion in C with an example.
    \item[(c)] How does a `for` loop work in C? Explain with an example.
    \item[(d)] Write a C program to calculate the factorial of a number using a recursive function.
    \item[(e)] Describe how C handles memory management, including stack and heap memory.
\end{enumerate}

\vspace{0.5cm}

\section*{Answer any three of the following \hfill 10x3=30}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] Discuss the advantages of using pointers in C, with an example of dynamic memory allocation.
    \item[(b)] Explain the differences between `call by value` and `call by reference` in C with examples.
    \item[(c)] What is file handling in C? Explain how to open, read, and close a file with an example program.
    \item[(d)] Discuss the concept of bitwise operators in C with examples of `AND`, `OR`, and `XOR`.
    \item[(e)] Explain the process of using functions in C. Write a program that uses functions to compute the area and perimeter of a rectangle.
\end{enumerate}

